  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The law of inertia, which is part of Newton's First Law of Motion, states that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by a net external force. In this context, inertia itself is not a force but a property of matter that quantifies its resistance to changes in motion.\n\nWhen considering the force applied by a body on an object due to inertia, we can infer that if the object is in a state of uniform motion or at rest, the net external force acting on it is zero. Therefore, the force applied by the body (due to inertia) is essentially not contributing to changing the state of motion of the object \u2014 the forces acting on the object are balanced.\n\nIf we want to discuss the force exerted by one object onto another (like a push or pull), this would be considered external and would not be described solely by inertia. The magnitude of that force would depend on how much force is actually applied by the body rather than being directly derived from the law of inertia. \n\nIn conclusion, inertia describes an object's resistance to changes in motion and doesn't define a specific force exerted. Forces acting on objects must be analyzed using Newton's laws of motion, where the sum of forces determines an object's acceleration or constant motion.",
